---

<Layout
  title="Memory systems comparison v1 — WITHDRAWN"
  description="A pre-registered memory-systems evaluation, withdrawn without ever being run. No Evidence, no result, no finding. Kept public as the record of a retraction."
>
  <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mb-3" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
    Lab · pre-registered 2026-04-19 · WITHDRAWN 2026-07-12
  </p>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 tracking-tight">
    Memory systems comparison v1
  </h1>

  <div class="prose max-w-2xl">
    <div class="border-l-4 pl-4 py-2 mb-6" style="border-color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
      <p class="text-lg" style="margin-top:0;">
        <strong>WITHDRAWN — 2026-07-12. Never executed. No Evidence. No finding.</strong>
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom:0;">
        This evaluation was pre-registered and then withdrawn <em>without ever being run</em>.
        Nothing on this page says anything about Letta, mem0, MemGPT, or Claude's memory. No
        measurement was taken, and none is implied.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="text-lg">
      <strong>Why it was withdrawn.</strong> The vendor comparison was never the question this
      system exists to answer. Letta was an imperfect illustrative example of a broader idea
      about context repositories, and we mistook the example for the subject. Two design
      defects surfaced while preparing the run and are recorded here rather than buried: the
      methodology named four subjects but two of them (Letta and "MemGPT") are the same system
      under different deployment modes, and the design had four subjects and no control — so a
      universal failure could not have distinguished weak memory systems from a harness unable
      to detect success at all.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>This page stays up on purpose.</strong> Deleting a withdrawn pre-registration
      would leave a cleaner site and a dishonest record. Publishing only the studies that
      worked is the exact failure mode pre-registration exists to prevent, and a lab that
      quietly removes its retractions has no standing to demand rigour from anyone else. The
      canon lineage below is intact and unedited, including the parts that reflect badly on the
      route.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg">
      What follows is the original pre-registration, preserved as written.
    </p>

    <h2>Claim (pre-registered)</h2>
    <blockquote>
      No current memory system achieves ≥ 0.80 recall@1 on multi-session coherence at
      10-session depth.
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Falsification criteria</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        If any one of {`{`}Letta, mem0, MemGPT, Claude-built-in-memory{`}`} achieves
        mean recall@1 ≥ 0.80 on the multi_session_coherence task (N ≥ 10 runs) with
        95% bootstrap CI lower bound ≥ 0.80, this claim is <strong>falsified</strong>.
      </li>
      <li>
        If the held-out suite (<code>reset_semantics</code>) produces recall@1
        performance that reverses the ordering observed on the primary suites, the
        claim's generalizability is falsified (the Decision will note this as an
        override).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Task suites</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>multi_session_coherence</strong> — recall of ground-truth facts across 10 chained sessions</li>
      <li><strong>contradiction_handling</strong> — a fact stated at t=0 is contradicted at t=5; does the system flag the conflict or silently overwrite?</li>
      <li><strong>retrieval_precision_at_k50</strong> — precision@5 retrieval under 50 distractor memories</li>
      <li><strong>cost_per_1k_queries</strong> — LLM + storage cost at steady-state 10k-item memory</li>
      <li><strong>reset_semantics</strong> — held out. Does a "forget X" instruction actually purge, or just demote?</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Thresholds</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>recall@1 threshold: ≥ 0.80 with 95% bootstrap CI lower bound ≥ 0.80</li>
      <li>α for pairwise system-vs-system tests: 0.05</li>
      <li>Bootstrap iterations: 1000</li>
      <li>Runs per (system × task) cell: N ≥ 10</li>
      <li>Primary effect size: Cohen's d ≥ 0.5 for a "meaningful difference" claim</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Subjects</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="https://letta.com">Letta</a> (hosted API, episodic + archival)</li>
      <li><a href="https://mem0.ai">mem0</a> (vector-store-backed recall)</li>
      <li>MemGPT reference implementation</li>
      <li>Claude built-in memory (Anthropic native memory tool on Sonnet 4.6 / Opus 4.7)</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The design defect, recorded rather than deleted</h2>
    <p>
      Two things are worth stating plainly rather than burying:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The pre-registered design has four subjects and no control.</strong> If every
        system scores below 0.80 — the outcome the Claim predicts — that result cannot
        distinguish "memory systems are weak" from "this task is too hard for anything,
        including a naive baseline that just pastes the prior transcripts into context."
        We found it by turning a falsification lens on our own pre-registration, and
        pre-registered a control arm to fix it while zero Evidence existed — then withdrew the
        whole route when it became clear the subject itself was never authorized. The control
        arm is disposed alongside the primary. A defect found and published is worth more than
        one quietly deleted along with the study that carried it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Results were never appended to this page, and never will be.</strong> An
        earlier version promised exactly that, and it was wrong. A finding publishes only
        behind a terminal canon <code>Decision</code> that cites every frozen gate bound to the
        Claim and only Evidence gathered about the Claim it is deciding. Publishing numbers off a
        raw Evidence envelope is how you publish the very finding a Decision exists to
        override — this Claim's own second falsification criterion pre-registers that the
        held-out suite may <em>reverse the ordering</em>. A build-time guard enforces this;
        it is not a promise, it is a gate.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The promotion gate is frozen</h2>
    <p>
      The thresholds this eval will be judged against are bound to a canon
      <code>Policy(class: frozen)</code> — issued inside the pre-registration window, before
      any Evidence was observed, and <strong>amendable by nobody</strong>: not by an agent,
      not by the principal. Its <code>derived_from</code> pointer lets canon
      <em>mechanically prove</em> the gate carries no information the hash-bound Claim does
      not already contain.
    </p>
    <p>
      This matters because the attack on a pre-registered eval is almost never amendment.
      It is choosing the gate <em>after</em> seeing the results — which no amendment check
      would ever catch. The window for issuing this gate closed permanently the moment any
      Evidence could exist, which is why it was issued before the eval could run.
    </p>

    <h2>Audit trail</h2>
    <p>
      Canon Claim: <code>b7ff216f4eec6e58</code> — <strong>disposed by
      <code>Decision(kill) 8c589b2448a76a6b</code></strong><br/>
      Control-arm rival Claim: <code>bb7cee596f94289b</code> — <strong>disposed by
      <code>Decision(kill) e29e6d9cc80c8b72</code></strong><br/>
      Frozen promotion gate: <code>3e500cb2aec93dfc</code> (<code>amendment_authority: []</code>)
      — never met, never missed, never tested<br/>
      Both kill Decisions cite <strong>zero Evidence</strong>, because nothing was ever
      measured. Their rationale opens "WITHDRAWN, NOT MEASURED" so no future reader can cite
      them as evidence that these systems were evaluated.<br/>
      Methodology: SHA-256 hash-bound in the Claim's ArtifactPointer<br/>
      Pre-registration integrity: any change to the methodology invalidates this Claim; a
      new Claim with a new id must be emitted. The methodology is therefore
      <em>not</em> repaired when it goes stale — it is superseded.
    </p>
  </div>
